With that football player nobody cared about Halacha so much, or his practice, just his stated identity... because his choice of identity and practice is and always will be about him, not me, or you. @JuliaCarmel__ ? Same same. It’s her life. Her story. Don’t judge.

He was in a public position. He played professional sports! And he said he was a Jew! How great! For G-d’s sake, we live in a time when people actually WANT to be publicly Jewish! It’s unreal. And almost unprecedented in our history.

I think about the guy the giants drafted last year. He wasn’t halachically Jewish by my standards, the guy had a Hebrew tattoo ffs (sorry, personal pet peeve, love you all even if you have tats) but he claimed Jewishness. And for so many, that was all that mattered!

It is precisely for the sake of Jews by choice who take the traditionally long road, like our author here, that the occasional outlier should not have their Jewishness questioned. And should questions arise, they are private (even for someone running for office).
To the exclusion of anyone who for any reason and in any way is deemed outside the standard.

This piece, is all judgement. The whole premise is off. @JuliaCarmel__ ‘s path and choices have zero, ZERO effect on the Jewishness of anyone else, especially any other new by choice. If they did, the whole system breaks down - because ultimately some standard will be the only 1
But that’s the important part, I say no because of the understanding of the law that I have committed to uphold. For my integrity. Mine. It’s never a judgement on someone else and their Jewish path.
If that never happened, then for my own integrity I would decline to perform the wedding.
Specifically, with immersion in a ritual bath built to standards of Jewish law and before a tribunal of rabbis or educated, practicing Jewish people.

That said, when someone engages me to say do their wedding; it’s my job to ask as to their Jewish history. And if they’ve converted I’ll need some kind of proof, and it would have had to be done in a manner consistent with Jewish law.
But I don’t want to live in that world.

First off, we’re just not supposed to question or judge or even talk about the ‘status’ of a convert. It undermines the whole concept. If someone can have their Jewishness questioned, than anyone can have their Jewishness questioned. Even the author of this piece.
